in our planet.

00:01:23.910 --> 00:01:25.330 align:middle line:90%
And it's all new science.

00:01:25.330 --> 00:01:28.640 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It has to do,
really, with human evolution.

00:01:28.640 --> 00:01:32.530 align:middle line:84%
You link the science and
biology to human evolution,

00:01:32.530 --> 00:01:34.666 align:middle line:90%
which is not an easy task.

00:01:34.666 --> 00:01:36.540 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Well, it's so
profoundly important.

00:01:36.540 --> 00:01:37.820 align:middle line:10%
Because up at this
point in time,

00:01:37.820 --> 00:01:39.300 align:middle line:10%
we really bought into
the belief that we're

00:01:39.300 --> 00:01:40.883 align:middle line:10%
more or less victims
of our heredity--

00:01:40.883 --> 00:01:41.610 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: OK.

00:01:41.610 --> 00:01:43.070 align:middle line:10%
>>LIPTON: --that we
didn't pick the genes,

00:01:43.070 --> 00:01:44.320 align:middle line:10%
and we can't change the genes.

00:01:44.320 --> 00:01:46.780 align:middle line:10%
And yet, these genes
control our characteristics.

00:01:46.780 --> 00:01:49.030 align:middle line:10%
And it turns out, the
new science reveals

00:01:49.030 --> 00:01:51.670 align:middle line:10%
this is a completely
false assumption

00:01:51.670 --> 00:01:55.910 align:middle line:10%
and that we are so profoundly
powerful, because not only do

00:01:55.910 --> 00:01:57.780 align:middle line:10%
we select and
activate our genes,

00:01:57.780 --> 00:02:01.270 align:middle line:10%
but we can modify our
gene expression just

00:02:01.270 --> 00:02:03.890 align:middle line:10%
by the way we respond to
life and perceive the world.

00:02:03.890 --> 00:02:06.100 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So in understanding
the new biology,

00:02:06.100 --> 00:02:08.340 align:middle line:84%
let's learn a little bit
about the old biology,

00:02:08.340 --> 00:02:10.440 align:middle line:84%
or the existing, I should
say, biology, science.

00:02:10.440 --> 00:02:11.110 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yeah.

00:02:11.110 --> 00:02:11.610 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:11.610 --> 00:02:13.530 align:middle line:84%
Well, I mean,
basically, we've all

00:02:13.530 --> 00:02:16.190 align:middle line:84%
been programmed with the belief
that this DNA-- the story

00:02:16.190 --> 00:02:18.810 align:middle line:84%
of DNA and the whole
history of DNA--

00:02:18.810 --> 00:02:23.240 align:middle line:84%
is a molecule that has the
blueprints for our lives built

00:02:23.240 --> 00:02:25.510 align:middle line:84%
into it and that
we receive this DNA

00:02:25.510 --> 00:02:26.805 align:middle line:90%
at the moment of conception.

00:02:26.805 --> 00:02:28.430 align:middle line:84%
And the rest of our
life is really just

00:02:28.430 --> 00:02:29.760 align:middle line:90%
an unfolding of the DNA.

00:02:29.760 --> 00:02:31.755 align:middle line:84%
So in one sense, your
life is essentially

00:02:31.755 --> 00:02:35.210 align:middle line:84%
preprogrammed in that belief
at the moment of conception.

00:02:35.210 --> 00:02:37.560 align:middle line:84%
The rest of it is just
unfolding the genes.

00:02:37.560 --> 00:02:39.420 align:middle line:84%
That belief, of
course, has led us

00:02:39.420 --> 00:02:42.310 align:middle line:84%
into believing that we are
powerless in controlling

00:02:42.310 --> 00:02:43.215 align:middle line:90%
our own health.

00:02:43.215 --> 00:02:46.980 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That we are subject
to our genetic upbringing

00:02:46.980 --> 00:02:48.440 align:middle line:90%
or our genetic code--

00:02:48.440 --> 00:02:49.070 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yes.

00:02:49.070 --> 00:02:51.200 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And that we have
to express that, right?

00:02:51.200 --> 00:02:51.900 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yeah.

00:02:51.900 --> 00:02:54.240 align:middle line:84%
And then, when we find, oh,
my goodness, maybe our genes

00:02:54.240 --> 00:02:56.120 align:middle line:84%
aren't operating correctly,
then all of a sudden,

00:02:56.120 --> 00:02:57.710 align:middle line:84%
we go outside of
ourselves and say,

00:02:57.710 --> 00:03:00.390 align:middle line:84%
I'm not powerful enough
to take care of my health.

00:03:00.390 --> 00:03:02.320 align:middle line:84%
I really have to seek
a rescuer, someone

00:03:02.320 --> 00:03:05.980 align:middle line:84%
who is going to guide me, help
me, and bring my health in,

00:03:05.980 --> 00:03:07.720 align:middle line:84%
because I can't
manage my own health.

00:03:07.720 --> 00:03:10.100 align:middle line:84%
And that's the belief system
we've been brought up with.

00:03:10.100 --> 00:03:12.986 align:middle line:84%
But it's a totally
incorrect assumption.

00:03:12.986 --> 00:03:14.860 align:middle line:84%
And that's why I get so
excited about talking

00:03:14.860 --> 00:03:15.695 align:middle line:90%
about this new biology.

00:03:15.695 --> 00:03:16.194 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:03:16.194 --> 00:03:18.653 align:middle line:84%
So let's learn a little bit
about the function of the cell.

00:03:18.653 --> 00:03:20.402 align:middle line:84%
We're going to empower
ourselves right now

00:03:20.402 --> 00:03:22.449 align:middle line:84%
to learn what's going
on inside our own body.

00:03:22.449 --> 00:03:22.990 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: OK.

00:03:22.990 --> 00:03:24.150 align:middle line:84%
Well, let's first
understand this.

00:03:24.150 --> 00:03:26.050 align:middle line:84%
When we look in a mirror and
see ourselves in the mirror,

00:03:26.050 --> 00:03:28.480 align:middle line:84%
and we see a single
individual looking back-- you

00:03:28.480 --> 00:03:30.938 align:middle line:84%
look in the mirror, and there's
that beautiful Lisa looking

00:03:30.938 --> 00:03:33.300 align:middle line:84%
back at yourself--
we see ourselves

00:03:33.300 --> 00:03:34.580 align:middle line:90%
as single individuals.

00:03:34.580 --> 00:03:37.370 align:middle line:90%
That is a total misperception.

00:03:37.370 --> 00:03:39.240 align:middle line:84%
Because in truth,
we are actually

00:03:39.240 --> 00:03:41.880 align:middle line:84%
made out of about
50 trillion cells.

00:03:41.880 --> 00:03:43.960 align:middle line:90%
The cells are the living entity.

00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:47.680 align:middle line:84%
A human, by full definition,
is a community of cells.

00:03:47.680 --> 00:03:52.227 align:middle line:84%
So when I say, Bruce, I'm really
speaking for 50 trillion cells.

00:03:52.227 --> 00:03:54.810 align:middle line:84%
So now you say, well, what about
these cells inside your body?

00:03:54.810 --> 00:03:57.220 align:middle line:84%
And I go, well,
interestingly enough,

00:03:57.220 --> 00:03:59.130 align:middle line:84%
if you look at the
average cell in your body,

00:03:59.130 --> 00:04:01.080 align:middle line:84%
you're going to find a
very interesting fact,

00:04:01.080 --> 00:04:01.788 align:middle line:90%
and that is this.

00:04:01.788 --> 00:04:03.970 align:middle line:84%
Now, we look at a
human and I say, well--

00:04:03.970 --> 00:04:05.950 align:middle line:84%
in a textbook of human
biology, I say, look

00:04:05.950 --> 00:04:08.800 align:middle line:84%
at all the human systems--
digestive, respiratory,

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:11.630 align:middle line:84%
excretory system, nervous
system, reproductive system, et

00:04:11.630 --> 00:04:14.570 align:middle line:84%
cetera, even immune
system-- and I say,

00:04:14.570 --> 00:04:17.490 align:middle line:84%
what's interesting is that
virtually every single cell

00:04:17.490 --> 00:04:19.760 align:middle line:84%
in our body has every one
of these systems in it.

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:21.880 align:middle line:84%
In other words,
whatever we can do,

00:04:21.880 --> 00:04:25.440 align:middle line:84%
we can only do it because
cells are doing it, OK?

00:04:25.440 --> 00:04:29.890 align:middle line:84%
Relevance, by definition, a cell
is a miniature human and that,

00:04:29.890 --> 00:04:34.330 align:middle line:84%
in our body-- our body is a
community of 50 trillion cells.

00:04:34.330 --> 00:04:36.150 align:middle line:84%
Our mind is more or
less a government.

00:04:36.150 --> 00:04:36.860 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:04:36.860 --> 00:04:39.570 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: If our government
is working in harmony

00:04:39.570 --> 00:04:41.840 align:middle line:84%
with the system, then
the 50 trillion cells

00:04:41.840 --> 00:04:44.990 align:middle line:84%
work together and create health
and happiness in your body.

00:04:44.990 --> 00:04:47.860 align:middle line:84%
If your government-- meaning
your mind, your thoughts,

00:04:47.860 --> 00:04:51.670 align:middle line:84%
and beliefs-- are not in harmony
with life or out of phase

00:04:51.670 --> 00:04:54.100 align:middle line:84%
or out of sync with what's
going on in the world, then,

00:04:54.100 --> 00:04:57.880 align:middle line:84%
by definition, it alters
and fractures the community,

00:04:57.880 --> 00:05:00.820 align:middle line:84%
and we express disease
and ill health.

00:05:00.820 --> 00:05:03.860 align:middle line:84%
So basically, health is
harmony in the system,

00:05:03.860 --> 00:05:07.020 align:middle line:84%
and disease is when the
community begins to break down.

00:05:07.020 --> 00:05:10.430 align:middle line:84%
We've had a tendency in our
history, blame the cells.

00:05:10.430 --> 00:05:12.110 align:middle line:84%
And it turns out,
oh, my goodness, no.

00:05:12.110 --> 00:05:13.940 align:middle line:84%
It's sort of
recognizing-- We have

00:05:13.940 --> 00:05:16.580 align:middle line:84%
to recognize our
responsibility in our thoughts

00:05:16.580 --> 00:05:19.060 align:middle line:84%
is because the new
science reveals

00:05:19.060 --> 00:05:22.380 align:middle line:84%
that our thoughts
actually control

00:05:22.380 --> 00:05:24.705 align:middle line:90%
our genetics and our biology.

00:05:24.705 --> 00:05:26.410 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You're basically
just describing

00:05:26.410 --> 00:05:27.850 align:middle line:84%
our entire political
environment,

00:05:27.850 --> 00:05:30.659 align:middle line:84%
our entire environmental
crisis that we're

00:05:30.659 --> 00:05:31.950 align:middle line:90%
going on with right now, right?

00:05:31.950 --> 00:05:34.636 align:middle line:84%
Exactly what you said, the
microcosm versus the macrocosm.

00:05:34.636 --> 00:05:36.510 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: It's not even
versus the macrocosm.

00:05:36.510 --> 00:05:39.260 align:middle line:84%
It's a microcosm and the
macrocosm are the same picture.

00:05:39.260 --> 00:05:41.260 align:middle line:84%
And that's because there
is an understanding

00:05:41.260 --> 00:05:43.920 align:middle line:84%
that our world, nature,
is built on something

00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:44.920 align:middle line:90%
called fractal geometry.

00:05:44.920 --> 00:05:47.170 align:middle line:84%
And you say, oh, well,
what the heck is that?

00:05:47.170 --> 00:05:49.540 align:middle line:84%
And I say, well, it's
a mathematics that

00:05:49.540 --> 00:05:53.010 align:middle line:84%
implies the existence
of as above, so below.

00:05:53.010 --> 00:05:55.290 align:middle line:84%
That is built in
to the mathematics.

00:05:55.290 --> 00:05:56.910 align:middle line:90%
The significance is--

00:05:56.910 --> 00:05:59.490 align:middle line:84%
That's why I say, if you see
cells as miniature humans,

00:05:59.490 --> 00:06:02.390 align:middle line:84%
and you see how they work, well,
the information about how they

00:06:02.390 --> 00:06:05.370 align:middle line:84%
work and how they communicate
applies to us as humans,

00:06:05.370 --> 00:06:07.794 align:middle line:84%
because we're just a
cell made by cells.

00:06:07.794 --> 00:06:09.460 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, let's
take a look at this.

00:06:09.460 --> 00:06:11.540 align:middle line:84%
Let's see what the cell looks
like and the functions of it.

00:06:11.540 --> 00:06:12.081 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: OK.

00:06:12.081 --> 00:06:14.410 align:middle line:84%
Well, interestingly enough,
we talk about single cells.

00:06:14.410 --> 00:06:15.910 align:middle line:84%
And we talk about
cells as, like,

00:06:15.910 --> 00:06:17.310 align:middle line:90%
the amoebas and stuff like that.

00:06:17.310 --> 00:06:18.989 align:middle line:84%
And I say, well, what
does a cell have?

00:06:18.989 --> 00:06:20.280 align:middle line:90%
Well, it has all the functions.

00:06:20.280 --> 00:06:22.480 align:middle line:10%
I say, but what
creates the cell?

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:24.635 align:middle line:10%
And what creates a cell is
things called proteins--

00:06:24.635 --> 00:06:25.285 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: OK.

00:06:25.285 --> 00:06:25.910 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: --OK?

00:06:25.910 --> 00:06:27.260 align:middle line:84%
And proteins are
the building blocks.

00:06:27.260 --> 00:06:29.230 align:middle line:10%
So if you want to build a
house, and you go to Home Depot,

00:06:29.230 --> 00:06:31.326 align:middle line:10%
and you've got all these
parts, and you collect

00:06:31.326 --> 00:06:32.950 align:middle line:10%
all these parts, you
can build a house,

00:06:32.950 --> 00:06:34.533 align:middle line:10%
and you build many
different versions.

00:06:34.533 --> 00:06:35.930 align:middle line:10%
Proteins are similar to that.

00:06:35.930 --> 00:06:38.900 align:middle line:10%
They are the building blocks
that create the cell, OK?

00:06:38.900 --> 00:06:41.215 align:middle line:10%
So basically, then,
your physical structure

00:06:41.215 --> 00:06:44.890 align:middle line:10%
is determined by
your proteins, OK?

00:06:44.890 --> 00:06:48.940 align:middle line:10%
And the proteins are
created from blueprints.

00:06:48.940 --> 00:06:50.580 align:middle line:10%
So the blueprints
are called the DNA.

00:06:50.580 --> 00:06:51.160 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: OK.

00:06:51.160 --> 00:06:52.160 align:middle line:10%
That's the genetic code.

00:06:52.160 --> 00:06:53.290 align:middle line:10%
>>LIPTON: That's
the genetic code,

00:06:53.290 --> 00:06:54.860 align:middle line:10%
and it gives us these proteins.

00:06:54.860 --> 00:06:57.790 align:middle line:84%
Now, what's really interesting
about the proteins is

00:06:57.790 --> 00:07:01.270 align:middle line:84%
that proteins-- each of about
the 150,000 different proteins

00:07:01.270 --> 00:07:02.930 align:middle line:84%
that make up a
human-- each protein

00:07:02.930 --> 00:07:05.520 align:middle line:84%
has its own unique shape and
its own unique structure.

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:08.186 align:middle line:84%
So as you assemble them, you get
all of the different variations

00:07:08.186 --> 00:07:10.040 align:middle line:90%
of life from these proteins, OK?

00:07:10.040 --> 00:07:12.580 align:middle line:84%
But now comes, what's
the secret of life?

00:07:12.580 --> 00:07:15.090 align:middle line:84%
And the secret of
life is that proteins

00:07:15.090 --> 00:07:18.240 align:middle line:84%
are capable of changing
their shape, OK?

00:07:18.240 --> 00:07:21.800 align:middle line:10%
So while we have 150,000
different proteins,

00:07:21.800 --> 00:07:24.050 align:middle line:10%
each with their own
shape, it turns out

00:07:24.050 --> 00:07:27.570 align:middle line:10%
that when this protein responds
to environmental information,

00:07:27.570 --> 00:07:30.780 align:middle line:10%
environmental signals, what's
going on in the environment.

00:07:30.780 --> 00:07:32.540 align:middle line:10%
Specific environmental
signals can

00:07:32.540 --> 00:07:34.390 align:middle line:10%
alter the shape of a protein.

00:07:34.390 --> 00:07:35.900 align:middle line:10%
So what we talk
about is, A, there

00:07:35.900 --> 00:07:37.530 align:middle line:10%
are proteins that
make up the body,

00:07:37.530 --> 00:07:40.310 align:middle line:10%
and, B, there are signals that
come from the environment.

00:07:40.310 --> 00:07:42.880 align:middle line:10%
When a signal
complements a protein,

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:45.550 align:middle line:10%
it causes the protein
to change shape.

00:07:45.550 --> 00:07:47.630 align:middle line:10%
Well, ah, that's
the secret of life.

00:07:47.630 --> 00:07:48.674 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: And that's what
we're taking a look at here

00:07:48.674 --> 00:07:49.424 align:middle line:10%
as it's happening?

00:07:49.424 --> 00:07:52.330 align:middle line:10%
>>LIPTON: Yeah, you're actually
watching proteins responding

00:07:52.330 --> 00:07:54.799 align:middle line:10%
and changing from shape
A to shape B in response

00:07:54.799 --> 00:07:55.840 align:middle line:10%
to environmental signals.

00:07:55.840 --> 00:07:57.620 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: And how is this
the secret of life?

00:07:57.620 --> 00:07:59.411 align:middle line:10%
>>LIPTON: Well, the
secret of life is this.

00:07:59.411 --> 00:08:01.780 align:middle line:10%
If proteins don't move,
then you are essentially

00:08:01.780 --> 00:08:04.260 align:middle line:10%
a physical body, a
cadaver more or less.

00:08:04.260 --> 00:08:04.830 align:middle line:10%
Why?

00:08:04.830 --> 00:08:07.569 align:middle line:10%
A body, a cadaver, a dead
body's got all the proteins,

00:08:07.569 --> 00:08:09.360 align:middle line:10%
got all the structure,
but there's no life.

00:08:09.360 --> 00:08:10.901 align:middle line:84%
I say, but where
does life come from?

00:08:10.901 --> 00:08:13.262 align:middle line:84%
Well, the fundamental
definition of life is movement.

00:08:13.262 --> 00:08:15.220 align:middle line:84%
I say, yeah, but where
does movement come from?

00:08:15.220 --> 00:08:20.190 align:middle line:84%
And then I go, proteins change
their shape, which is movement.

00:08:20.190 --> 00:08:23.110 align:middle line:84%
And what the cells do
is use the movement

00:08:23.110 --> 00:08:26.110 align:middle line:84%
and harness the movement
to carry out the functions.

00:08:26.110 --> 00:08:29.619 align:middle line:84%
Respiration, digestion, muscle
contraction, for example,

00:08:29.619 --> 00:08:31.160 align:middle line:84%
is changing the
shape of the protein.

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:33.179 align:middle line:90%
So where does life come from?

00:08:33.179 --> 00:08:36.730 align:middle line:84%
Signals engaging with the
proteins changing the shape,

00:08:36.730 --> 00:08:39.569 align:middle line:84%
and then the shape movement
is used to do work.

00:08:39.569 --> 00:08:41.610 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So it's our
responses to the environment.

00:08:41.610 --> 00:08:42.230 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: To the environment.

00:08:42.230 --> 00:08:42.870 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:08:42.870 --> 00:08:43.659 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Right.

00:08:43.659 --> 00:08:45.722 align:middle line:84%
If you cut off the response
to the environment,

00:08:45.722 --> 00:08:47.680 align:middle line:84%
so the cell doesn't
respond to the environment,

00:08:47.680 --> 00:08:49.510 align:middle line:90%
the proteins stop moving.

00:08:49.510 --> 00:08:52.890 align:middle line:84%
A cell that cannot respond to
the environment is almost like

00:08:52.890 --> 00:08:54.870 align:middle line:90%
a person that's comatose.

00:08:54.870 --> 00:08:57.110 align:middle line:84%
They're still alive,
but there's no behavior.

00:08:57.110 --> 00:08:59.500 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So as our cells are
operating and replicating

00:08:59.500 --> 00:09:02.870 align:middle line:84%
and replicating, the
environmental senses

00:09:02.870 --> 00:09:07.390 align:middle line:84%
that come in with thoughts
or foods or other type

00:09:07.390 --> 00:09:10.485 align:middle line:84%
of environmental factors
are what shape our cells?

00:09:10.485 --> 00:09:13.575 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Well, yeah, actually,
it's the environmental factors.

00:09:13.575 --> 00:09:14.950 align:middle line:84%
And again, as you
mentioned, it's

00:09:14.950 --> 00:09:16.550 align:middle line:84%
a whole list of
environmental factors.

00:09:16.550 --> 00:09:19.250 align:middle line:84%
There are physical factors,
such as the nutrition

00:09:19.250 --> 00:09:20.230 align:middle line:90%
that we're eating.

00:09:20.230 --> 00:09:24.390 align:middle line:84%
But there are also energetic
factors, such as consciousness

00:09:24.390 --> 00:09:27.090 align:middle line:84%
or what's going on in the
field-- electromagnetic fields.

00:09:27.090 --> 00:09:30.440 align:middle line:84%
Like cell phones are creating
electromagnetic fields,

00:09:30.440 --> 00:09:32.170 align:middle line:84%
which interact with
our proteins and can

00:09:32.170 --> 00:09:34.850 align:middle line:90%
influence our own biology.

00:09:34.850 --> 00:09:37.470 align:middle line:84%
So we're starting to see
that we are responding

00:09:37.470 --> 00:09:39.700 align:middle line:84%
to a whole network
of information

00:09:39.700 --> 00:09:41.200 align:middle line:84%
from the environment,
which includes

00:09:41.200 --> 00:09:43.880 align:middle line:84%
both physical and
energetic components.

00:09:43.880 --> 00:09:46.260 align:middle line:84%
Now, you then have
to say, well, how

00:09:46.260 --> 00:09:49.860 align:middle line:84%
does the cell organize
this behavior?

00:09:49.860 --> 00:09:51.840 align:middle line:84%
Because without
organization, it would just

00:09:51.840 --> 00:09:53.257 align:middle line:84%
be a bunch of stuff
moving around.

00:09:53.257 --> 00:09:54.298 align:middle line:90%
But it's all coordinated.

00:09:54.298 --> 00:09:54.865 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Hm.

00:09:54.865 --> 00:09:57.090 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Well, there's
the equivalent of a brain.

00:09:57.090 --> 00:10:00.710 align:middle line:84%
And the equivalent of the
brain is the cell membrane.

00:10:00.710 --> 00:10:03.040 align:middle line:90%
And it's the cell's skin.

00:10:03.040 --> 00:10:07.175 align:middle line:84%
And it's very interesting,
because what I've talked about

00:10:07.175 --> 00:10:10.005 align:middle line:84%
in relating a cell to a human is
that cells are, by definition,

00:10:10.005 --> 00:10:11.370 align:middle line:90%
miniature humans.

00:10:11.370 --> 00:10:13.480 align:middle line:84%
And the characteristic
and structure of the cells

00:10:13.480 --> 00:10:14.540 align:middle line:90%
relate to our own.

00:10:14.540 --> 00:10:16.220 align:middle line:84%
Where we have
organs in our body,

00:10:16.220 --> 00:10:19.590 align:middle line:84%
the cell has miniature
organs called organelles, OK?

00:10:19.590 --> 00:10:22.360 align:middle line:84%
And it's interesting,
because the membrane, or skin

00:10:22.360 --> 00:10:25.210 align:middle line:84%
of the cell, is the
equivalent of the brain.

00:10:25.210 --> 00:10:27.570 align:middle line:84%
We used to think it was
the nucleus with the genes,

00:10:27.570 --> 00:10:29.910 align:middle line:84%
because we'd say, oh,
genes control this,

00:10:29.910 --> 00:10:31.690 align:middle line:90%
and genes control that.

00:10:31.690 --> 00:10:33.210 align:middle line:90%
But genes are blueprints.

00:10:33.210 --> 00:10:34.900 align:middle line:84%
And this is what we
really have to get

00:10:34.900 --> 00:10:36.590 align:middle line:90%
people to fully understand.

00:10:36.590 --> 00:10:39.690 align:middle line:84%
A blueprint has no
self-actualization.

00:10:39.690 --> 00:10:41.065 align:middle line:84%
It's just a piece
of information.

00:10:41.065 --> 00:10:42.387 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: A flat blueprint.

00:10:42.387 --> 00:10:43.220 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: That's it.

00:10:43.220 --> 00:10:43.353 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:10:43.353 --> 00:10:43.420 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:10:43.420 --> 00:10:45.649 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: And so, you say,
well, a gene turned on

00:10:45.649 --> 00:10:46.565 align:middle line:90%
and a gene turned off.

00:10:46.565 --> 00:10:48.972 align:middle line:84%
And I say, do blueprints
turn on and turn off?

00:10:48.972 --> 00:10:50.680 align:middle line:84%
And the answer is no,
they don't do that.

00:10:50.680 --> 00:10:51.385 align:middle line:90%
They're just information.

00:10:51.385 --> 00:10:52.950 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Not without
something to construct it.

00:10:52.950 --> 00:10:54.210 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: That's right.

00:10:54.210 --> 00:10:56.710 align:middle line:84%
So to make a
construction, you have

00:10:56.710 --> 00:10:58.040 align:middle line:90%
blueprints, which are plans.

00:10:58.040 --> 00:10:59.165 align:middle line:90%
But you have a contractor--

00:10:59.165 --> 00:10:59.665 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Ah.

00:10:59.665 --> 00:11:03.030 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: --who selects the
blueprints and organizes how

00:11:03.030 --> 00:11:05.970 align:middle line:84%
they interact and build the
structure from the blueprints,

00:11:05.970 --> 00:11:06.605 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:11:06.605 --> 00:11:09.005 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So we are the
contractors of our cells?

00:11:09.005 --> 00:11:11.620 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Well, what it turns
out is the nervous system--

00:11:11.620 --> 00:11:12.295 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Ah.

00:11:12.295 --> 00:11:13.670 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: --is the contractor.

00:11:13.670 --> 00:11:14.650 align:middle line:90%
And how does it work?

00:11:14.650 --> 00:11:16.750 align:middle line:84%
It reads those
environmental signals

00:11:16.750 --> 00:11:19.410 align:middle line:84%
that are around us,
translates the signals

00:11:19.410 --> 00:11:23.080 align:middle line:84%
into biological information
which goes to the cells,

00:11:23.080 --> 00:11:25.290 align:middle line:84%
and then that information
controls the behavior.

00:11:25.290 --> 00:11:27.750 align:middle line:84%
So in our model of
the cell, for example,

00:11:27.750 --> 00:11:31.420 align:middle line:84%
if I add some new
chemistry, like hormones,

00:11:31.420 --> 00:11:35.020 align:middle line:84%
to a culture dish, the chemistry
sort of rains on the cells.

00:11:35.020 --> 00:11:35.660 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:11:35.660 --> 00:11:37.285 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: And then
some of the hormones

00:11:37.285 --> 00:11:39.340 align:middle line:84%
stick to the cell's
surface, the skin.

00:11:39.340 --> 00:11:43.770 align:middle line:84%
And the skin, the membrane,
reads this information

00:11:43.770 --> 00:11:45.330 align:middle line:84%
through what are
called receptors.

00:11:45.330 --> 00:11:48.220 align:middle line:84%
And I go, again, well,
it's just like a human.

00:11:48.220 --> 00:11:51.117 align:middle line:84%
Our skin is actually the
source of our nervous system.

00:11:51.117 --> 00:11:52.825 align:middle line:84%
And this is what we
know from embryology.

00:11:52.825 --> 00:11:54.075 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's a giant membrane.

00:11:54.075 --> 00:11:55.910 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: It's a
giant membrane, and it

00:11:55.910 --> 00:11:58.250 align:middle line:84%
has receptors--
eyes, ears, nose--

00:11:58.250 --> 00:12:01.340 align:middle line:84%
and we read the environmental
signals through these receptors

00:12:01.340 --> 00:12:04.450 align:middle line:84%
and then respond to these
signals with our behavior.

00:12:04.450 --> 00:12:07.200 align:middle line:84%
The cell, a miniature
version of that,

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:09.070 align:middle line:84%
has receptors built
into the membrane

00:12:09.070 --> 00:12:10.840 align:middle line:84%
to read the
environmental signals.

00:12:10.840 --> 00:12:13.640 align:middle line:84%
And when the signals show
up at the cell membrane,

00:12:13.640 --> 00:12:16.260 align:middle line:84%
the cell membrane, just
like the nervous system,

00:12:16.260 --> 00:12:18.290 align:middle line:84%
distributes the signals
throughout the body

00:12:18.290 --> 00:12:19.900 align:middle line:90%
of the cell.

00:12:19.900 --> 00:12:23.750 align:middle line:84%
And these signals, like I showed
in the last slide, when signals

00:12:23.750 --> 00:12:26.866 align:middle line:84%
are sent into the
cell, the proteins

00:12:26.866 --> 00:12:29.240 align:middle line:84%
and their complementary signals,
when they come together,

00:12:29.240 --> 00:12:30.750 align:middle line:90%
cause the proteins to move.

00:12:30.750 --> 00:12:34.375 align:middle line:84%
The movement generates
respiration, or digestion,

00:12:34.375 --> 00:12:35.875 align:middle line:84%
or any of the
functions of the cell.

00:12:35.875 --> 00:12:36.950 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Or replication.

00:12:36.950 --> 00:12:39.420 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Ah, that's the
important part, replication.

00:12:39.420 --> 00:12:40.410 align:middle line:90%
And it goes like this.

00:12:40.410 --> 00:12:42.390 align:middle line:84%
Oh, the signals
affect the proteins.

00:12:42.390 --> 00:12:43.950 align:middle line:84%
But then, you
might say, but what

00:12:43.950 --> 00:12:47.040 align:middle line:84%
if I need a protein to
respond to a signal,

00:12:47.040 --> 00:12:48.940 align:middle line:84%
but I don't have that
protein in the cell?

00:12:48.940 --> 00:12:50.700 align:middle line:84%
Well, that's the
next exciting part.

00:12:50.700 --> 00:12:53.077 align:middle line:84%
So he says, well, where
do you get the protein

00:12:53.077 --> 00:12:54.660 align:middle line:84%
to make a response
to the environment?

00:12:54.660 --> 00:12:58.160 align:middle line:84%
And the answer is, the
DNA are the blueprints.

00:12:58.160 --> 00:13:02.690 align:middle line:84%
So the cell membrane sends
a signal in to the cell,

00:13:02.690 --> 00:13:05.460 align:middle line:84%
to the nucleus,
and then activates

00:13:05.460 --> 00:13:06.445 align:middle line:90%
expression of the gene.

00:13:06.445 --> 00:13:08.486 align:middle line:90%
Well, why is that so relevant?

00:13:08.486 --> 00:13:10.180 align:middle line:90%
And the answer is very simple.

00:13:10.180 --> 00:13:14.050 align:middle line:84%
Is that the environmental signal
is what engages and activates

00:13:14.050 --> 00:13:16.920 align:middle line:84%
the gene, not the gene
activating itself.

00:13:16.920 --> 00:13:19.280 align:middle line:84%
Well, this is a whole
new field of science.

00:13:19.280 --> 00:13:21.200 align:middle line:84%
So just to let
people know, we're

00:13:21.200 --> 00:13:23.630 align:middle line:84%
moving beyond genetics
as a field of science.

00:13:23.630 --> 00:13:27.200 align:middle line:84%
And the new field of science
is called signal transduction.

00:13:27.200 --> 00:13:28.490 align:middle line:90%
It's a complicated name.

00:13:28.490 --> 00:13:30.640 align:middle line:84%
But what it says
is, can we follow

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:33.084 align:middle line:84%
how a signal from the
environment enters a cell

00:13:33.084 --> 00:13:34.250 align:middle line:90%
and then engages a function?

00:13:34.250 --> 00:13:35.740 align:middle line:90%
And that's signal transduction.

00:13:35.740 --> 00:13:37.940 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So now this
could explain disease.

00:13:37.940 --> 00:13:39.980 align:middle line:84%
And one of the Facebook
questions coming in

00:13:39.980 --> 00:13:41.970 align:middle line:90%
is, how do you explain disease?

00:13:41.970 --> 00:13:44.350 align:middle line:84%
So you have this gene,
you have this cell,

00:13:44.350 --> 00:13:46.090 align:middle line:90%
that may have the cancer gene.

00:13:46.090 --> 00:13:48.150 align:middle line:84%
And it could lay dormant
for years and years

00:13:48.150 --> 00:13:48.900 align:middle line:90%
and forever maybe.

00:13:48.900 --> 00:13:49.566 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Right.

00:13:49.566 --> 00:13:52.190 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But then the outside
environmental signal that comes

00:13:52.190 --> 00:13:55.956 align:middle line:84%
in could be stress, toxins,
food, negative thinking--

00:13:55.956 --> 00:13:56.830 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Absolutely.

00:13:56.830 --> 00:13:57.790 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --activates the gene?

00:13:57.790 --> 00:13:59.070 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: That's what
activates the gene.

00:13:59.070 --> 00:14:00.310 align:middle line:84%
That's why when you
say, well, somebody

00:14:00.310 --> 00:14:02.327 align:middle line:84%
says I have a cancer
gene, I say, now, wait.

00:14:02.327 --> 00:14:04.660 align:middle line:84%
If you had a cancer gene,
then you should have a cancer.

00:14:04.660 --> 00:14:07.302 align:middle line:84%
And then I go, but when
we look at the statistics,

00:14:07.302 --> 00:14:09.010 align:middle line:84%
everybody that has
so-called cancer genes

00:14:09.010 --> 00:14:10.060 align:middle line:90%
doesn't have cancer.

00:14:10.060 --> 00:14:12.900 align:middle line:84%
So then you have to ask the very
more important question about,

00:14:12.900 --> 00:14:16.520 align:middle line:84%
well, how can I be-- you
know, possess a cancer gene

00:14:16.520 --> 00:14:17.490 align:middle line:90%
and not have a cancer?

00:14:17.490 --> 00:14:20.584 align:middle line:84%
And the answer is, because the
gene doesn't activate itself.

00:14:20.584 --> 00:14:22.500 align:middle line:84%
And that's why, let's
say, a doctor would say,

00:14:22.500 --> 00:14:23.999 align:middle line:84%
well, you have this
particular gene,

00:14:23.999 --> 00:14:25.250 align:middle line:90%
and you have a propensity.

00:14:25.250 --> 00:14:28.164 align:middle line:84%
67% of the people
will express a cancer.

00:14:28.164 --> 00:14:29.830 align:middle line:84%
And then I go, well,
that's interesting.

00:14:29.830 --> 00:14:34.040 align:middle line:84%
But I really want to know, the
33% that have this same gene

00:14:34.040 --> 00:14:36.890 align:middle line:84%
and don't have the cancer,
that's more important.

00:14:36.890 --> 00:14:38.912 align:middle line:84%
Because it's what is
different in their life,

00:14:38.912 --> 00:14:40.620 align:middle line:84%
because they have a
gene, but they're not

00:14:40.620 --> 00:14:42.360 align:middle line:90%
effecting a disease with it.

00:14:42.360 --> 00:14:46.260 align:middle line:84%
And it turns out is it's not
the possession of the gene.

00:14:46.260 --> 00:14:49.070 align:middle line:84%
It's the response to
the environment that

00:14:49.070 --> 00:14:52.370 align:middle line:84%
will send signals
to engage the gene.

00:14:52.370 --> 00:14:54.710 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And so if you
have stress coming

00:14:54.710 --> 00:14:58.050 align:middle line:84%
into the environment, it
creates a cascading effects

00:14:58.050 --> 00:14:59.065 align:middle line:90%
of chemicals--

00:14:59.065 --> 00:14:59.910 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yes.

00:14:59.910 --> 00:15:02.619 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --that then activate
the cancer and the gene.

00:15:02.619 --> 00:15:04.660 align:middle line:84%
Of course, then it replicates
into cancer, right?

00:15:04.660 --> 00:15:05.326 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Right.

00:15:05.326 --> 00:15:09.380 align:middle line:84%
And this cascade of chemistry,
that goes from the environment

00:15:09.380 --> 00:15:11.775 align:middle line:84%
to the gene, part of it
is signal transduction.

00:15:11.775 --> 00:15:13.740 align:middle line:84%
But there is a
special part, where

00:15:13.740 --> 00:15:15.880 align:middle line:84%
the signal leaves the
cytoplasm of the cell

00:15:15.880 --> 00:15:18.700 align:middle line:84%
but goes into the nucleus
where the genes are and affects

00:15:18.700 --> 00:15:19.570 align:middle line:90%
a heredity.

00:15:19.570 --> 00:15:21.940 align:middle line:84%
That's a new science
called epigenetics.

00:15:21.940 --> 00:15:24.020 align:middle line:84%
And this is the
revolution in science.

00:15:24.020 --> 00:15:25.480 align:middle line:90%
Because basically, it says this.

00:15:25.480 --> 00:15:27.150 align:middle line:84%
What did we all learn in
school, and what did I

00:15:27.150 --> 00:15:28.620 align:middle line:84%
teach early on in
medical school?

00:15:28.620 --> 00:15:30.420 align:middle line:84%
It was something
called genetic control.

00:15:30.420 --> 00:15:33.280 align:middle line:84%
It simply means
control by genes.

00:15:33.280 --> 00:15:35.850 align:middle line:84%
The new science with
signal transduction

00:15:35.850 --> 00:15:38.700 align:middle line:90%
is called epigenetic control.

00:15:38.700 --> 00:15:41.010 align:middle line:84%
And you say, well,
what does that mean?

00:15:41.010 --> 00:15:42.670 align:middle line:84%
And I say, that
little epi, E-P-I--

00:15:42.670 --> 00:15:43.952 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Uh, huh?

00:15:43.952 --> 00:15:46.080 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: --it
really means above.

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:49.040 align:middle line:84%
So if I say genetic control,
controlled by genes,

00:15:49.040 --> 00:15:55.140 align:middle line:84%
and I say epigenetic control,
it says control above the genes,

00:15:55.140 --> 00:15:58.990 align:middle line:84%
and now we're beginning to
recognize what really controls

00:15:58.990 --> 00:16:01.697 align:middle line:84%
the genes is not the
genes, but the signals

00:16:01.697 --> 00:16:03.280 align:middle line:84%
from the environment
control the gene.

00:16:03.280 --> 00:16:05.447 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Now, when you were
teaching medical school--

00:16:05.447 --> 00:16:06.029 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yes?

00:16:06.029 --> 00:16:08.470 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --and you were teaching
basically the old science,

00:16:08.470 --> 00:16:12.130 align:middle line:84%
according to you, were you
able to infuse these teachings

00:16:12.130 --> 00:16:14.710 align:middle line:84%
into what you were talking
about in your professor days?

00:16:14.710 --> 00:16:16.190 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Well, it
was interesting.

00:16:16.190 --> 00:16:18.190 align:middle line:84%
Because when I started
out in my professor days,

00:16:18.190 --> 00:16:20.590 align:middle line:84%
I was a conventional
biologist, OK?

00:16:20.590 --> 00:16:23.280 align:middle line:84%
But my research
was on stem cells.

00:16:23.280 --> 00:16:26.670 align:middle line:84%
And this was,
like, 45 years ago.

00:16:26.670 --> 00:16:27.285 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:16:27.285 --> 00:16:29.701 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: So at that time,
there were just a handful of us

00:16:29.701 --> 00:16:31.290 align:middle line:84%
in the entire world
that even knew

00:16:31.290 --> 00:16:32.860 align:middle line:90%
what a stem cell was really.

00:16:32.860 --> 00:16:34.526 align:middle line:84%
And a stem cell
is the equivalent

00:16:34.526 --> 00:16:36.400 align:middle line:84%
of an embryonic cell,
and it's in our bodies.

00:16:36.400 --> 00:16:37.810 align:middle line:90%
And all of us have stem cells.

00:16:37.810 --> 00:16:39.060 align:middle line:90%
And the reason is simply this.

00:16:39.060 --> 00:16:42.830 align:middle line:84%
Every day we lose
hundreds of billions

00:16:42.830 --> 00:16:46.896 align:middle line:84%
of cells due to wear and tear
and normal aging processes,

00:16:46.896 --> 00:16:48.020 align:middle line:90%
and that becomes important.

00:16:48.020 --> 00:16:49.850 align:middle line:84%
It says, well, if you're
losing hundreds of billions

00:16:49.850 --> 00:16:52.410 align:middle line:84%
of cells every day, how long
would it be before you're dead?

00:16:52.410 --> 00:16:53.285 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right, right.

00:16:53.285 --> 00:16:54.900 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: And the
answer's, well, no.

00:16:54.900 --> 00:16:56.050 align:middle line:90%
Because we replace them.

00:16:56.050 --> 00:16:57.630 align:middle line:84%
And then I say,
well, then what's

00:16:57.630 --> 00:16:59.463 align:middle line:84%
replacing all of these
cells that are dying?

00:16:59.463 --> 00:17:01.870 align:middle line:84%
And the answer is
these embryonic stem

00:17:01.870 --> 00:17:04.382 align:middle line:84%
cells are providing
for all the new cells.

00:17:04.382 --> 00:17:06.215 align:middle line:84%
So all of us have stem
cells if we're alive.

00:17:06.215 --> 00:17:06.960 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Uh, huh.

00:17:06.960 --> 00:17:08.110 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Because otherwise,
we wouldn't be alive.

00:17:08.110 --> 00:17:08.730 align:middle line:90%
That's a good start.

00:17:08.730 --> 00:17:09.750 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: We have a
certain amount, right?

00:17:09.750 --> 00:17:10.940 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yeah, OK?

00:17:10.940 --> 00:17:12.874 align:middle line:84%
And the significance
is, so what is

00:17:12.874 --> 00:17:14.290 align:middle line:84%
it that controls
these stem cells?

00:17:14.290 --> 00:17:18.240 align:middle line:84%
So I'm teaching medical students
the conventional curriculum.

00:17:18.240 --> 00:17:20.950 align:middle line:84%
Yes, genes control
the fate of the cells.

00:17:20.950 --> 00:17:24.319 align:middle line:84%
And at the same time, I
am cloning stem cells.

00:17:24.319 --> 00:17:25.730 align:middle line:90%
And what does that really mean?

00:17:25.730 --> 00:17:30.470 align:middle line:84%
Well, cloning stem cells means
I take one isolated stem cell

00:17:30.470 --> 00:17:33.350 align:middle line:84%
and put it into a culture
dish all by itself.

00:17:33.350 --> 00:17:35.620 align:middle line:84%
And every 10 to 12
hours, a cell divides.

00:17:35.620 --> 00:17:36.522 align:middle line:90%
So I put in one cell.

00:17:36.522 --> 00:17:37.230 align:middle line:90%
Then there's two.

00:17:37.230 --> 00:17:38.530 align:middle line:90%
Then's their four, eight.

00:17:38.530 --> 00:17:40.040 align:middle line:90%
And it doubles and doubles.

00:17:40.040 --> 00:17:41.570 align:middle line:84%
And after a week
or two, I've got

00:17:41.570 --> 00:17:43.200 align:middle line:84%
thousands of cells
in the petri dish.

00:17:43.200 --> 00:17:43.700 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:17:43.700 --> 00:17:44.850 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Well, that's
not the experiment.

00:17:44.850 --> 00:17:46.110 align:middle line:90%
That's just getting ready.

00:17:46.110 --> 00:17:47.735 align:middle line:84%
But what that means
is, what do I have?

00:17:47.735 --> 00:17:51.210 align:middle line:84%
I have thousands of
genetically identical cells,

00:17:51.210 --> 00:17:52.880 align:middle line:84%
because they came
from one parent.

00:17:52.880 --> 00:17:56.130 align:middle line:84%
Every cell is just a
clone of the parent.

00:17:56.130 --> 00:17:58.340 align:middle line:84%
So I have thousands of
genetically identical cells.

00:17:58.340 --> 00:17:59.450 align:middle line:90%
Now I do the experiment.

00:17:59.450 --> 00:17:59.950 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:17:59.950 --> 00:18:02.924 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: I take some of the
cells out of my culture dish

00:18:02.924 --> 00:18:04.465 align:middle line:84%
and put it into
another culture dish,

00:18:04.465 --> 00:18:05.673 align:middle line:90%
and I change the environment.

00:18:05.673 --> 00:18:06.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:18:06.330 --> 00:18:06.945 align:middle line:90%
What do you change?

00:18:06.945 --> 00:18:09.050 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Well, the environment
is the culture medium.

00:18:09.050 --> 00:18:11.008 align:middle line:84%
And you have to recognize,
cells are like fish.

00:18:11.008 --> 00:18:12.140 align:middle line:90%
They live in fluid.

00:18:12.140 --> 00:18:13.775 align:middle line:84%
And so if you have
fish in an aquarium,

00:18:13.775 --> 00:18:16.233 align:middle line:84%
you have to provide them with
food and the right pH and all

00:18:16.233 --> 00:18:16.355 align:middle line:90%
these things.

00:18:16.355 --> 00:18:17.040 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --pH in the environment.

00:18:17.040 --> 00:18:17.870 align:middle line:90%
I see.

00:18:17.870 --> 00:18:21.170 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: So I adjust my culture
medium to feed the cells.

00:18:21.170 --> 00:18:23.440 align:middle line:84%
And what I do is I
make some minor changes

00:18:23.440 --> 00:18:24.800 align:middle line:90%
in the chemistry of that.

00:18:24.800 --> 00:18:26.870 align:middle line:10%
And when I take some
cells out of my main dish,

00:18:26.870 --> 00:18:28.575 align:middle line:10%
put them in this new dish--
let's call it environment A--

00:18:28.575 --> 00:18:29.140 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: OK.

00:18:29.140 --> 00:18:30.560 align:middle line:10%
>>LIPTON: The cells form muscle.

00:18:30.560 --> 00:18:31.560 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: OK.

00:18:31.560 --> 00:18:33.160 align:middle line:10%
>>LIPTON: But here's
the experiment.

00:18:33.160 --> 00:18:36.190 align:middle line:10%
I go back to the original dish,
with the original stem cells,

00:18:36.190 --> 00:18:39.050 align:middle line:10%
take some more out but
put them in petri dish

00:18:39.050 --> 00:18:41.500 align:middle line:10%
B with a different
environment, environment B.

00:18:41.500 --> 00:18:43.460 align:middle line:10%
And in this dish,
they form bone.

00:18:43.460 --> 00:18:47.140 align:middle line:10%
And I go back, go get some more
cells out of the original dish,

00:18:47.140 --> 00:18:50.130 align:middle line:10%
put it in dish C with a
different environment, C,

00:18:50.130 --> 00:18:51.420 align:middle line:10%
and they form fat cells.

00:18:51.420 --> 00:18:54.540 align:middle line:10%
And then you're left with
a very simple question.

00:18:54.540 --> 00:18:57.450 align:middle line:10%
What controls the
fate of the cells?

00:18:57.450 --> 00:18:59.050 align:middle line:10%
Well, the first thing is this.

00:18:59.050 --> 00:19:01.420 align:middle line:10%
They're all
genetically identical.

00:19:01.420 --> 00:19:05.160 align:middle line:84%
So it wasn't the genes that made
the difference between bone,

00:19:05.160 --> 00:19:07.040 align:middle line:90%
muscle, and fat.

00:19:07.040 --> 00:19:08.700 align:middle line:90%
It was the environment.

00:19:08.700 --> 00:19:11.950 align:middle line:84%
And what was interesting, here
I am teaching students genes

00:19:11.950 --> 00:19:14.830 align:middle line:84%
control life, and the
cells are teaching me.

00:19:14.830 --> 00:19:17.620 align:middle line:84%
No, the cells learn,
that they respond

00:19:17.620 --> 00:19:20.830 align:middle line:84%
to the environmental information
and adjust their genes

00:19:20.830 --> 00:19:22.920 align:middle line:90%
to match the environment, OK?

00:19:22.920 --> 00:19:25.084 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So the individual
cells in there,

00:19:25.084 --> 00:19:27.000 align:middle line:84%
although they came from
the same host, changed

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:28.245 align:middle line:90%
based on the environment.

00:19:28.245 --> 00:19:29.052 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yeah.

00:19:29.052 --> 00:19:30.760 align:middle line:84%
They were all genetically
identical, too.

00:19:30.760 --> 00:19:34.180 align:middle line:84%
So you can't say, oh,
genes made me become this,

00:19:34.180 --> 00:19:36.040 align:middle line:84%
or genes made me
become that, OK?

00:19:36.040 --> 00:19:38.552 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So it's the outside
environment that changes it.

00:19:38.552 --> 00:19:40.010 align:middle line:84%
But there's an
interesting question

00:19:40.010 --> 00:19:40.765 align:middle line:90%
coming in from Facebook.

00:19:40.765 --> 00:19:41.389 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yeah?

00:19:41.389 --> 00:19:45.690 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: James says, how do you
explain that beliefs can change

00:19:45.690 --> 00:19:48.850 align:middle line:84%
certain parts of DNA, but
others it can't change,

00:19:48.850 --> 00:19:51.569 align:middle line:84%
such as height, eye color,
those types of things?

00:19:51.569 --> 00:19:53.610 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Well, that may
not be necessarily true.

00:19:53.610 --> 00:19:56.100 align:middle line:84%
For example, we know that
in multiple personalities,

00:19:56.100 --> 00:19:59.110 align:middle line:84%
that in personality A, a
person can have blue eyes,

00:19:59.110 --> 00:20:01.250 align:middle line:84%
and in personality B,
they can have grey eyes--

00:20:01.250 --> 00:20:02.000 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Seriously?

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:02.680 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yeah, seriously.

00:20:02.680 --> 00:20:03.480 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:20:03.480 --> 00:20:05.110 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: --and many
different changes.

00:20:05.110 --> 00:20:06.820 align:middle line:84%
So for example,
in personality A,

00:20:06.820 --> 00:20:11.630 align:middle line:84%
a person may have an allergic
response to strawberries

00:20:11.630 --> 00:20:13.190 align:middle line:84%
and then switch
to personality B,

00:20:13.190 --> 00:20:15.735 align:middle line:84%
and a minute later, they
could eat strawberries

00:20:15.735 --> 00:20:16.860 align:middle line:90%
without any problem at all.

00:20:16.860 --> 00:20:19.970 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So you could
effectively, with your mind,

00:20:19.970 --> 00:20:21.145 align:middle line:90%
control allergies?

00:20:21.145 --> 00:20:22.470 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yes.

00:20:22.470 --> 00:20:25.010 align:middle line:84%
Most allergies are
actually really associated

00:20:25.010 --> 00:20:26.820 align:middle line:90%
with a mind aspect, as well.

00:20:26.820 --> 00:20:28.729 align:middle line:84%
But there's a
developmental part that we

00:20:28.729 --> 00:20:29.770 align:middle line:90%
can't get into right now.

00:20:29.770 --> 00:20:31.260 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Right now,
right, but yes.

00:20:31.260 --> 00:20:32.700 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: But it's interesting.

00:20:32.700 --> 00:20:35.680 align:middle line:84%
There's an old story, like,
of a couple going out.

00:20:35.680 --> 00:20:38.580 align:middle line:84%
And the guy is in
love with this woman.

00:20:38.580 --> 00:20:40.380 align:middle line:90%
And she has a dog.

00:20:40.380 --> 00:20:42.490 align:middle line:84%
And that's part of
the relationship.

00:20:42.490 --> 00:20:44.270 align:middle line:90%
And then they have a breakup.

00:20:44.270 --> 00:20:46.640 align:middle line:84%
And after the breakup,
the guy, all of a sudden,

00:20:46.640 --> 00:20:48.135 align:middle line:90%
has an allergy to dogs.

00:20:48.135 --> 00:20:49.750 align:middle line:90%
He never had an allergy to dogs.

00:20:49.750 --> 00:20:50.333 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I see.

00:20:50.333 --> 00:20:52.090 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: It's a
psychological consequence

00:20:52.090 --> 00:20:54.465 align:middle line:84%
of connecting the dog with
the relationship and the break

00:20:54.465 --> 00:20:55.440 align:middle line:90%
of that relationship.

00:20:55.440 --> 00:20:58.449 align:middle line:84%
And the pathology of the
allergy is a reflection

00:20:58.449 --> 00:20:59.990 align:middle line:84%
of the breaking of
that relationship.

00:20:59.990 --> 00:21:02.140 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So that's
just another example

00:21:02.140 --> 00:21:04.870 align:middle line:84%
of how the environment
affects the cells.

00:21:04.870 --> 00:21:06.122 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Oh, absolutely.

00:21:06.122 --> 00:21:07.580 align:middle line:84%
And one of the
things I really like

00:21:07.580 --> 00:21:11.140 align:middle line:84%
to get people to understand is,
I have a plastic dish of cells.

00:21:11.140 --> 00:21:12.975 align:middle line:84%
I put these cells in
a good environment,

00:21:12.975 --> 00:21:15.280 align:middle line:84%
and they grow, and they
flourish, and they're healthy,

00:21:15.280 --> 00:21:16.510 align:middle line:90%
and it's really great.

00:21:16.510 --> 00:21:18.290 align:middle line:84%
And then I say, look,
just take the dish

00:21:18.290 --> 00:21:20.248 align:middle line:84%
from the good environment
and move it over here

00:21:20.248 --> 00:21:21.300 align:middle line:90%
to a bad environment.

00:21:21.300 --> 00:21:24.310 align:middle line:84%
And immediately, what happens
is the cells start to get sick,

00:21:24.310 --> 00:21:25.540 align:middle line:90%
and they begin to die.

00:21:25.540 --> 00:21:28.100 align:middle line:84%
Now, if I had a
specialist doctor

00:21:28.100 --> 00:21:31.770 align:middle line:84%
who was a cell doctor in our
conventional world of health,

00:21:31.770 --> 00:21:34.575 align:middle line:84%
he would look at my cells
in the sick culture.

00:21:34.575 --> 00:21:36.480 align:middle line:84%
And he goes, oh, my
god, Bruce, your cells

00:21:36.480 --> 00:21:38.450 align:middle line:90%
need some medicine, some drugs.

00:21:38.450 --> 00:21:41.510 align:middle line:84%
And then I would
go, absolutely not.

00:21:41.510 --> 00:21:43.180 align:middle line:90%
And the reason why is this.

00:21:43.180 --> 00:21:45.850 align:middle line:84%
To bring health back to the
cells, I don't give them drugs.

00:21:45.850 --> 00:21:48.626 align:middle line:84%
All I do is take them
from the bad environment,

00:21:48.626 --> 00:21:50.500 align:middle line:84%
move them right back to
the good environment.

00:21:50.500 --> 00:21:54.000 align:middle line:84%
They will instantaneously
recover and become healthy

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:54.700 align:middle line:90%
again.

00:21:54.700 --> 00:21:58.360 align:middle line:84%
The simple point is, since
the environment is influencing

00:21:58.360 --> 00:22:01.980 align:middle line:84%
the genetic activity, a
healthy environment elicits

00:22:01.980 --> 00:22:05.000 align:middle line:84%
a healthy response,
and an environment

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:07.270 align:middle line:84%
that's not in harmony
with our biology

00:22:07.270 --> 00:22:09.246 align:middle line:84%
will elicit a
pathological response.

00:22:09.246 --> 00:22:11.370 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, so then why
do they give chemotherapy

00:22:11.370 --> 00:22:14.850 align:middle line:84%
to people who have cancer
with the cell replicating

00:22:14.850 --> 00:22:17.120 align:middle line:84%
in its dysfunctional
state and dying?

00:22:17.120 --> 00:22:18.070 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yeah.

00:22:18.070 --> 00:22:19.630 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: What is the
purpose of that?

00:22:19.630 --> 00:22:21.171 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Well, the
old belief system

00:22:21.171 --> 00:22:23.720 align:middle line:90%
is, these cells are rogue cells.

00:22:23.720 --> 00:22:25.260 align:middle line:90%
Their genes went crazy.

00:22:25.260 --> 00:22:26.650 align:middle line:90%
And so we blame the genes.

00:22:26.650 --> 00:22:27.550 align:middle line:90%
We blame the cells.

00:22:27.550 --> 00:22:29.330 align:middle line:90%
And we say, kill the cells.

00:22:29.330 --> 00:22:31.660 align:middle line:84%
And it's really a
very terrible thing,

00:22:31.660 --> 00:22:33.300 align:middle line:84%
if you think about
it in this regard.

00:22:33.300 --> 00:22:34.760 align:middle line:90%
And that is this.

00:22:34.760 --> 00:22:37.660 align:middle line:84%
Chemotherapy kills
cells that are dividing.

00:22:37.660 --> 00:22:38.400 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:22:38.400 --> 00:22:41.390 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Well, you live
every day because you

00:22:41.390 --> 00:22:43.410 align:middle line:84%
have stem cells that
have to divide to replace

00:22:43.410 --> 00:22:45.740 align:middle line:84%
the hundreds of billions of
cells you lose every day.

00:22:45.740 --> 00:22:48.240 align:middle line:84%
When you give a
patient chemotherapy,

00:22:48.240 --> 00:22:49.790 align:middle line:84%
does the chemotherapy
distinguish

00:22:49.790 --> 00:22:53.490 align:middle line:84%
between the necessary healthy
stem cells and the rogue cancer

00:22:53.490 --> 00:22:53.990 align:middle line:90%
cells?

00:22:53.990 --> 00:22:55.200 align:middle line:90%
And the answer is no.

00:22:55.200 --> 00:22:57.690 align:middle line:84%
And so when you are
doing chemotherapy,

00:22:57.690 --> 00:22:59.710 align:middle line:84%
not only are you killing
the cancer cells, which

00:22:59.710 --> 00:23:02.220 align:middle line:84%
was the intention,
but you are also

00:23:02.220 --> 00:23:04.140 align:middle line:84%
debilitating the
individual, because you're

00:23:04.140 --> 00:23:05.690 align:middle line:84%
killing their own
stem cells, which

00:23:05.690 --> 00:23:07.190 align:middle line:90%
they need for their health.

00:23:07.190 --> 00:23:09.970 align:middle line:84%
So chemotherapy is not the
best approach to kill those.

00:23:09.970 --> 00:23:13.400 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, could you do it in
addition to what you're talking

00:23:13.400 --> 00:23:16.890 align:middle line:84%
about in terms of changing the
environment with your thoughts,

00:23:16.890 --> 00:23:18.960 align:middle line:84%
with your mental
health, with your food,

00:23:18.960 --> 00:23:20.040 align:middle line:90%
with different types of--

00:23:20.040 --> 00:23:20.650 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: This is
what we're finding.

00:23:20.650 --> 00:23:22.280 align:middle line:90%
Here's a great story.

00:23:22.280 --> 00:23:24.604 align:middle line:84%
Dean Ornish, a
wonderful physician,

00:23:24.604 --> 00:23:27.020 align:middle line:84%
who has done a lot of research,
recently published a paper

00:23:27.020 --> 00:23:29.944 align:middle line:84%
where he took prostate
cancer patients.

00:23:29.944 --> 00:23:31.110 align:middle line:90%
And he took a group of them.

00:23:31.110 --> 00:23:34.515 align:middle line:84%
And he said, look, for 90 days,
no drugs, no chemotherapy,

00:23:34.515 --> 00:23:35.890 align:middle line:84%
and none of this
stuff like this.

00:23:35.890 --> 00:23:37.560 align:middle line:84%
What are we going
to do for 90 days?

00:23:37.560 --> 00:23:39.240 align:middle line:90%
We're going to change your diet.

00:23:39.240 --> 00:23:41.520 align:middle line:84%
We're going to give you
stress reduction techniques.

00:23:41.520 --> 00:23:43.546 align:middle line:84%
We're going to teach
you how to meditate,

00:23:43.546 --> 00:23:44.920 align:middle line:84%
and gave them just
some lifestyle

00:23:44.920 --> 00:23:46.280 align:middle line:90%
changes like that, right?

00:23:46.280 --> 00:23:51.580 align:middle line:84%
The significance was in
90 days, 500 genes changed

00:23:51.580 --> 00:23:53.430 align:middle line:90%
their function and their action.

00:23:53.430 --> 00:23:55.380 align:middle line:84%
And many of those
genes were related

00:23:55.380 --> 00:23:57.510 align:middle line:84%
to the development of
the prostate cancer.

00:23:57.510 --> 00:24:00.060 align:middle line:84%
What it had shown was, you
didn't have to give them drugs.

00:24:00.060 --> 00:24:04.190 align:middle line:84%
You just had to return them to
a more harmonious environment,

00:24:04.190 --> 00:24:05.910 align:middle line:84%
an environment that's
very supportive

00:24:05.910 --> 00:24:07.860 align:middle line:90%
of their natural life state.

00:24:07.860 --> 00:24:09.990 align:middle line:84%
And the genes automatically
reverted back.

00:24:09.990 --> 00:24:12.410 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So when your
doctor tells you to get rid

00:24:12.410 --> 00:24:15.292 align:middle line:84%
of the stress in your life,
he's really trying to tell you,

00:24:15.292 --> 00:24:16.916 align:middle line:84%
this is the way of
healing essentially.

00:24:16.916 --> 00:24:18.041 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Well, absolutely.

00:24:18.041 --> 00:24:19.970 align:middle line:84%
Because the American
Psychological Association

00:24:19.970 --> 00:24:23.710 align:middle line:84%
has now revealed that up
to 90% of doctor visits

00:24:23.710 --> 00:24:25.310 align:middle line:90%
are due to stress.

00:24:25.310 --> 00:24:27.161 align:middle line:84%
And it's the stress
that interferes with us.

00:24:27.161 --> 00:24:29.660 align:middle line:84%
A lot of people think, well,
my genes are causing my issues.

00:24:29.660 --> 00:24:31.410 align:middle line:84%
And it goes, well, you
know, let's correct

00:24:31.410 --> 00:24:33.440 align:middle line:90%
a very important point here.

00:24:33.440 --> 00:24:34.530 align:middle line:90%
And that is this.

00:24:34.530 --> 00:24:37.390 align:middle line:84%
Less than 5% of the
people on this planet

00:24:37.390 --> 00:24:39.990 align:middle line:84%
arrived here with
genetic defects

00:24:39.990 --> 00:24:42.529 align:middle line:84%
that would impact a negative
thing on their life, OK?

00:24:42.529 --> 00:24:43.070 align:middle line:90%
Less than 5%.

00:24:43.070 --> 00:24:43.890 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really?

00:24:43.890 --> 00:24:44.540 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Yeah.

00:24:44.540 --> 00:24:49.080 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So that means
95% of the people

00:24:49.080 --> 00:24:52.509 align:middle line:84%
don't have to necessarily
express their genetic makeup?

00:24:52.509 --> 00:24:53.300 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Well, no.

00:24:53.300 --> 00:24:54.510 align:middle line:84%
They express their
genetic makeup,

00:24:54.510 --> 00:24:55.620 align:middle line:90%
but it's not pathological.

00:24:55.620 --> 00:24:56.210 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: But it's not.

00:24:56.210 --> 00:24:56.709 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:24:56.709 --> 00:24:59.580 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: 95% of us got here
with a completely wonderful set

00:24:59.580 --> 00:25:01.580 align:middle line:84%
of genes to have a
healthy, happy existence.

00:25:01.580 --> 00:25:03.610 align:middle line:84%
And then you say, well,
I can understand the 5%,

00:25:03.610 --> 00:25:05.420 align:middle line:84%
and we can talk about
them, because they still

00:25:05.420 --> 00:25:07.000 align:middle line:84%
can be influenced
in a different way.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:08.500 align:middle line:84%
But the 95% of the
people that start

00:25:08.500 --> 00:25:10.708 align:middle line:84%
getting illness, and they
were the ones that got here

00:25:10.708 --> 00:25:12.790 align:middle line:84%
with a healthy set of
genes, how can we start off

00:25:12.790 --> 00:25:15.260 align:middle line:84%
by blaming the genes
as the problem?

00:25:15.260 --> 00:25:20.080 align:middle line:84%
And now what we know is, not
only does the environment

00:25:20.080 --> 00:25:23.340 align:middle line:84%
select the genes, through the
signals from the environment,

00:25:23.340 --> 00:25:25.770 align:middle line:84%
but the environmental
signals can

00:25:25.770 --> 00:25:28.310 align:middle line:90%
modify the reading of the gene.

00:25:28.310 --> 00:25:31.560 align:middle line:84%
Now, here's a number that
is, like, mind-boggling.

00:25:31.560 --> 00:25:33.610 align:middle line:84%
A gene is a blueprint
to make a protein, which

00:25:33.610 --> 00:25:35.080 align:middle line:90%
is a building block of the body.

00:25:35.080 --> 00:25:35.746 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Uh, huh.

00:25:35.746 --> 00:25:38.520 align:middle line:84%
>>LIPTON: Depending on how you
respond to the environment,

00:25:38.520 --> 00:25:41.180 align:middle line:84%
you can create
thousands of variations

00:25:41.180 --> 00:25:44.640 align:middle line:84%
of proteins from the
same gene blueprint

00:25:44.640 --> 00:25:46.880 align:middle line:84%
just by the way you
respond to the environment.

00:25:46.880 --> 00:25:48.950 align:middle line:84%
And out of those
thousands, some of them

00:25:48.950 --> 00:25:52.519 align:middle line:84%
might be good interpretations
of the gene blueprint,

00:25:52.519 --> 00:25:54.810 align:middle line:84%
and some of them might be
pathological interpretations.

00:25:54.810 --> 00:25:59.380 align:middle line:84%
So when we talked about
cancer, 90% of cancer

00:25:59.380 --> 00:26:01.550 align:middle line:90%
is not based on heredity.

00:26:01.550 --> 00:26:06.190 align:middle line:84%
90% of cancer is based on
having normal genes that,

00:26:06.190 --> 00:26:08.390 align:middle line:84%
through environmental
interactions that are not

00:26:08.390 --> 00:26:11.630 align:middle line:84%
in harmony, are then reading
as a pathological gene.

00:26:11.630 --> 00:26:13.380 align:middle line:84%
It's not the gene that
caused the problem.

00:26:13.380 --> 00:26:15.570 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And it's
also our perception

00:26:15.570 --> 00:26:17.352 align:middle line:90%
of that particular event.

00:26:17.352 --> 00:26:18.810 align:middle line:84%
You could have
stress in your life.

00:26:18.810 --> 00:26:21.160 align:middle line:84%
But your perception
of the stress

00:26:21.160 --> 00:26:24.002 align:middle line:84%
affects the environment
of the gene.

00:26:24.002 --> 00:26:25.210 align:middle line:90%
>>LIPTON: Of the genes, yeah.

00:26:25.210 --> 00:26:26.750 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: We're going
to take a quick break.

00:26:26.750 --> 00:26:28.708 align:middle line:84%
But I want to come back
to that, because that's

00:26:28.708 --> 00:26:30.040 align:middle line:90%
a huge teaching within itself.

00:26:30.040 --> 00:26:32.670 align:middle line:84%
Dr. Bruce Lipton is my
guest, cellular biologist.

00:26:32.670 --> 00:26:35.600 align:middle line:84%
We're going to come back and
